			<h4><a rel="nofollow" id="comment_link_64967633" name="comment_link_64967633" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23530061&amp;cid=64967633" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64967633)" >Re:Author Accused of Faking Punctuation</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64967633" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64967633); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~easyTree">easyTree</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~easyTree">( 1042254 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64967633">		
		on Saturday November 23, 2024 @09:28PM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23530061&amp;cid=64967633">#64967633</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64967633"><blockquote><div><p>Hello Claude: Please give come examples of metonymy involving 'numbers' - e.g 'faking numbers'</p></div></blockquote><p>Let me explore some examples and uses of metonymy involving "numbers":<br>Metonymy with "numbers" often involves using the word "numbers" to represent broader concepts related to data, statistics, finances, or mathematical calculations. Some common examples:<br>"The numbers don't lie" - referring to statistical evidence or data as a whole<br>"Faking/cooking/massaging the numbers" - representing fraudulent accounting or dishonest reporting<br>"Running the numbers" - representing the entire process of calculating or analyzing data<br>"The numbers are looking good" - representing overall financial performance or statistics<br>"Living by the numbers" - representing a life strictly governed by statistics, schedules, or quantitative measures<br>"Behind the numbers" - representing the deeper meaning or context of statistics<br>"Chase the numbers" - representing pursuit of statistical or financial targets<br>"Let's see the numbers" - representing all relevant data or financial information<br>"The numbers person" - representing someone who excels at or focuses on mathematical/analytical work<br>In each case, "numbers" acts as a stand-in for a more complex system or process related to quantitative information. The metonymy works because numbers are a concrete, tangible aspect of these abstract systems, making them an effective representational shorthand.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64967633">
